{
  "text": "Members of the M . tuberculosis family have a single rrn operon (K. E. Kempsell, I. C. E. Estrada-G, M. J. Colson & R. A. Cox, unpublished work). They also have fewer ribosomes than many other bacteria. However, their complement of ribosomes varies according to the growth rate [CITATION_1] . More than 80% of the RNA fraction of a bacterium is rRNA, so that the ribosome complement is reflected in the RNA:DNA ratio. In the mid-exponential phase this ratio is 2 : l for M . tuberculosis, 4 : 1 for Mycobacterium smegmatis and 20:l for E. coli [CITATION_2] , that is the complement of ribosomes are in the proportions 1 : 2 : 10. M . tuberculosis has a single rrn operon, M . smegmatis has two (Bercovier et al., 1986 ) and E. coli has seven (Kiss et  al., 1977) . The single operon of M . tuberculosis provides about 70% of the number of ribosomes synthesized by one operon of E. coli, on the basis of the assumption that the seven operons are equivalent. The evidence that M . tuberculosis maintains growth-rate-dependent control of ribosome biosynthesis rests on the observation that the RNA : DNA ratio varies according to growth conditions whereas the ratio RNA : protein remains unchanged [CITATION_3] . The sequence data presented above for M . tuberculosis has similarities with elements of the promoter and leader regions of the rrn operons of B. subtilis and E . coli, suggesting that they have similar mechanisms for the control of rRNA synthesis.",
  "correct_citation": {
